# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: dramatiq
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:dramatiq/advanced-message-queuing-protocol] The **Advanced Message Queuing Protocol** (**AMQP**) is an open standard application layer protocol for message-oriented middleware.
[src:dramatiq/advanced-message-queuing-protocol] The defining features of AMQP are message orientation, queuing, routing (including point-to-point and publish-and-subscribe), reliability and security.
[src:dramatiq/advanced-message-queuing-protocol] AMQP mandates the behavior of the messaging provider and client to the extent that implementations from different vendors are interoperable, in the same way as SMTP, HTTP, FTP, etc. have created interoperable systems.
[src:dramatiq/advanced-message-queuing-protocol] Previous standardizations of middleware have happened at the API level (e.g.
[src:dramatiq/advanced-message-queuing-protocol] JMS) and were focused on standardizing programmer interaction with different middleware implementations, rather than on providing interoperability between multiple implementations.
[src:dramatiq/advanced-message-queuing-protocol] Unlike JMS, which defines an API and a set of behaviors that a messaging implementation must provide, AMQP is a wire-level protocol.
[src:dramatiq/advanced-message-queuing-protocol] A wire-level protocol is a description of the format of the data that is sent across the network as a stream of bytes.
[src:dramatiq/advanced-message-queuing-protocol] Consequently, any tool that can create and interpret messages that conform to this data format can interoperate with any other compliant tool irrespective of implementation language.
[src:dramatiq/advanced-message-queuing-protocol] AMQP is a binary application layer protocol, designed to efficiently support a wide variety of messaging applications and communication patterns.
[src:dramatiq/advanced-message-queuing-protocol] It assumes an underlying reliable transport layer protocol such as Transmission Control Protocol (TCP).
[src:dramatiq/advanced-message-queuing-protocol] AMQP was originated in 2003 by John O'Hara at JPMorgan Chase in London.
[src:dramatiq/advanced-message-queuing-protocol] AMQP was conceived as a co-operative open effort.
[src:dramatiq/advanced-message-queuing-protocol] The initial design was by JPMorgan Chase from mid-2004 to mid-2006 and it contracted iMatix Corporation to develop a C broker and protocol documentation.
[src:dramatiq/advanced-message-queuing-protocol] In 2005 JPMorgan Chase approached other firms to form a working group that included Cisco Systems, IONA Technologies, iMatix, Red Hat, and Transaction Workflow Innovation Standards Team (TWIST).
[src:dramatiq/advanced-message-queuing-protocol] In the same year JPMorgan Chase partnered with Red Hat to create Apache Qpid, initially in Java and soon after C++.
[src:dramatiq/advanced-message-queuing-protocol] Independently, RabbitMQ was developed in Erlang by Rabbit Technologies, followed later by the Microsoft and StormMQ implementations.
[src:dramatiq/advanced-message-queuing-protocol] In 2008, Pieter Hintjens, CEO and chief software designer of iMatix, wrote an article called "What is wrong with AMQP (and how to fix it)" and distributed it to the working group to alert of imminent failure, identify problems seen by iMatix and propose ways to fix the AMQP specification.
[src:dramatiq/advanced-message-queuing-protocol] By then, iMatix had already started work on ZeroMQ.
[src:dramatiq/advanced-message-queuing-protocol] In 2010, Hintjens announced that iMatix would leave the AMQP workgroup and did not plan to support AMQP/1.0 in favor of the significantly simpler and faster ZeroMQ.
[src:dramatiq/advanced-message-queuing-protocol] In August 2011, the AMQP working group announced its reorganization into an OASIS member section.
[src:dramatiq/advanced-message-queuing-protocol] AMQP 1.0 was released by the AMQP working group on 30 October 2011, at a conference in New York.
[src:dramatiq/advanced-message-queuing-protocol] At the event Microsoft, Red Hat, VMware, Apache, INETCO and IIT Software demonstrated software running the protocol in an interoperability demonstration.
[src:dramatiq/advanced-message-queuing-protocol] The next day, on 1 November 2011, the formation of an OASIS Technical Committee was announced to advance this contributed AMQP version 1.0 through the international open standards process.
[src:dramatiq/advanced-message-queuing-protocol] The first draft from OASIS was released in February 2012, the changes as compared to that published by the Working Group being restricted to edits for improved clarity (no functional changes).
[src:dramatiq/advanced-message-queuing-protocol] The second draft was released for public review on 20 June (again with no functional changes), and AMQP was approved as an OASIS standard on 31 October 2012.
[src:dramatiq/advanced-message-queuing-protocol] OASIS AMQP was approved for release as an ISO and IEC International Standard in April 2014.
[src:dramatiq/advanced-message-queuing-protocol] AMQP 1.0 was balloted through the Joint Technical Committee on Information Technology (JTC1) of the International Standards Organization (ISO) and the International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC).
[src:dramatiq/advanced-message-queuing-protocol] The approved OASIS AMQP submission has been given the designation, ISO/IEC 19464.
[src:dramatiq/advanced-message-queuing-protocol] Previous versions of AMQP were 0-8, published in June 2006, 0-9, published in December 2006, 0-10 published in February 2008 and 0-9-1, published in November 2008.
[src:dramatiq/advanced-message-queuing-protocol] These earlier releases are significantly different from the 1.0 specification.
[src:dramatiq/advanced-message-queuing-protocol] Whilst AMQP originated in the financial services industry, it has general applicability to a broad range of middleware problems.
[src:dramatiq/advanced-message-queuing-protocol] AMQP defines a self-describing encoding scheme allowing interoperable representation of a wide range of commonly used types.
[src:dramatiq/advanced-message-queuing-protocol] It also allows typed data to be annotated with additional meaning, for example a particular string value might be annotated so that it could be understood as a URL.
[src:dramatiq/advanced-message-queuing-protocol] Likewise a map value containing key-value pairs for 'name', 'address' etc., might be annotated as being a representation of a 'customer' type.
[src:dramatiq/advanced-message-queuing-protocol] The type-system is used to define a message format allowing standard and extended meta-data to be expressed and understood by processing entities.
[src:dramatiq/advanced-message-queuing-protocol] It is also used to define the communication primitives through which messages are exchanged between such entities, i.e. the AMQP *frame bodies*.
[src:dramatiq/advanced-message-queuing-protocol] The basic unit of data in AMQP is a *frame*.
[src:dramatiq/advanced-message-queuing-protocol] There are nine AMQP frame bodies defined that are used to initiate, control and tear down the transfer of messages between two peers.
[src:dramatiq/advanced-message-queuing-protocol] The *link protocol* is at the heart of AMQP.
[src:dramatiq/advanced-message-queuing-protocol] An *attach* frame body is sent to initiate a new link; a *detach* to tear down a link.
[src:dramatiq/advanced-message-queuing-protocol] Links may be established in order to receive or send messages.
[src:dramatiq/advanced-message-queuing-protocol] Messages are sent over an established *link* using the *transfer* frame.
[src:dramatiq/advanced-message-queuing-protocol] Messages on a link flow in only one direction.
[src:dramatiq/advanced-message-queuing-protocol] Transfers are subject to a credit-based flow control scheme, managed using *flow* frames.
[src:dramatiq/advanced-message-queuing-protocol] This allows a process to protect itself from being overwhelmed by too large a volume of messages or more simply to allow a subscribing link to pull messages as and when desired.
[src:dramatiq/advanced-message-queuing-protocol] Each transferred message must eventually be *settled*.
[src:dramatiq/advanced-message-queuing-protocol] Settlement ensures that the sender and receiver agree on the state of the transfer, providing reliability guarantees.
[src:dramatiq/advanced-message-queuing-protocol] Changes in state and settlement for a transfer (or set of transfers) are communicated between the peers using the *disposition* frame.
[src:dramatiq/advanced-message-queuing-protocol] Various reliability guarantees can be enforced this way: at-most-once, at-least-once and exactly-once.
[src:dramatiq/advanced-message-queuing-protocol] Multiple links, in both directions, can be grouped together in a *session*.
[src:dramatiq/advanced-message-queuing-protocol] A session is a bidirectional, sequential conversation between two peers that is initiated with a *begin* frame and terminated with an *end* frame.
[src:dramatiq/advanced-message-queuing-protocol] A connection between two peers can have multiple sessions multiplexed over it, each logically independent.
[src:dramatiq/advanced-message-queuing-protocol] Connections are initiated with an *open* frame in which the sending peer's capabilities are expressed, and terminated with a *close* frame.
[src:dramatiq/advanced-message-queuing-protocol] AMQP defines as the *bare message*, that part of the message that is created by the sending application.
[src:dramatiq/advanced-message-queuing-protocol] This is considered immutable as the message is transferred between one or more processes.
[src:dramatiq/advanced-message-queuing-protocol] Ensuring the message as sent by the application is immutable allows for end-to-end message signing and/or encryption and ensures that any integrity checks (e.g. hashes or digests) remain valid.
[src:dramatiq/advanced-message-queuing-protocol] The message can be annotated by intermediaries during transit, but any such annotations are kept distinct from the immutable *bare message*.
[src:dramatiq/advanced-message-queuing-protocol] Annotations may be added before or after the bare message.
[src:dramatiq/advanced-message-queuing-protocol] The *header* is a standard set of delivery-related annotations that can be requested or indicated for a message and includes time to live, durability, priority.
[src:dramatiq/advanced-message-queuing-protocol] Properties are specified in the AMQP type system, as are annotations.
[src:dramatiq/advanced-message-queuing-protocol] The application data can be of any form, and in any encoding the application chooses.
[src:dramatiq/advanced-message-queuing-protocol] One option is to use the AMQP type system to send structured, self-describing data.
[src:dramatiq/advanced-message-queuing-protocol] The link protocol transfers messages between two *nodes* but assumes very little as to what those nodes are or how they are implemented.
[src:dramatiq/advanced-message-queuing-protocol] A key category is those nodes used as a *rendezvous point* between senders and receivers of messages (e.g.
[src:dramatiq/advanced-message-queuing-protocol] The AMQP specification calls such nodes *distribution nodes* and codifies some common behaviors.
[src:dramatiq/advanced-message-queuing-protocol] Though AMQP can be used in simple peer-to-peer systems, defining this framework for messaging capabilities additionally enables interoperability with messaging intermediaries (brokers, bridges etc.) in larger, richer messaging networks.
[src:dramatiq/advanced-message-queuing-protocol] The framework specified covers basic behaviors but allows for extensions to evolve that can be further codified and standardised.
[src:dramatiq/advanced-message-queuing-protocol] AMQP protocol version 1.0 is the current specification version.
[src:dramatiq/advanced-message-queuing-protocol] It focuses on core features which are necessary for interoperability at Internet scale.
[src:dramatiq/advanced-message-queuing-protocol] It contains less explicit routing than previous versions because core functionality is the first to be rigorously standardized.
[src:dramatiq/advanced-message-queuing-protocol] AMQP 1.0 interoperability has been more extensively tested with more implementors than prior versions.
[src:dramatiq/advanced-message-queuing-protocol] The AMQP website contains the OASIS specification for version 1.0.
[src:dramatiq/advanced-message-queuing-protocol] Java Message Service (JMS), is often compared to AMQP.
[src:dramatiq/advanced-message-queuing-protocol] However, JMS is an API specification (part of the Java EE specification) that defines how message producers and consumers are implemented.
[src:dramatiq/advanced-message-queuing-protocol] JMS does not guarantee interoperability between implementations, and the JMS-compliant messaging system in use may need to be deployed on both client and server.
[src:dramatiq/advanced-message-queuing-protocol] On the other hand, AMQP is a wire-level protocol specification.
[src:dramatiq/advanced-message-queuing-protocol] In theory AMQP provides interoperability as different AMQP-compliant software can be deployed on the client and server sides.
[src:dramatiq/guide] We just grab the response content at that URL and print out how many space-separated chunks there are in that response.
[src:dramatiq/guide] Doing so immediately enqueues a message (via our local RabbitMQ server) that can be processed asynchronously but *doesn’t actually run the function*.
[src:dramatiq/guide] In order to run it, we’ll have to boot up a Dramatiq worker.
[src:dramatiq/guide] Because all messages have to be sent over the network, any arguments you send to an actor must be JSON-encodable.
[src:dramatiq/guide] Dramatiq comes with a command line utility called, predictably, `dramatiq`.
[src:dramatiq/guide] This utility is able to spin up multiple concurrent worker processes that pop messages off the queue and send them to actor functions for execution.
[src:dramatiq/guide] This will spin up as many processes as there are CPU cores on your machine with 8 worker threads per process.
[src:dramatiq/guide] Run `dramatiq -h` if you want to see a list of the available command line flags.
[src:dramatiq/guide] At this point, you’re probably wondering what happens if you send the actor an invalid URL.
[src:dramatiq/guide] Dramatiq assumes all actors are idempotent so when an exception occurs during message processing, it automatically enqueues a retry for that message with exponential backoff.
[src:dramatiq/guide] Dramatiq will keep retrying the message with longer and longer delays in between runs until we fix our code or for up to about 30 days from when it was first enqueued.
[src:dramatiq/guide] Substitute the process ID of your own main process for `13047`.
[src:dramatiq/guide] You can find the PID by looking at the log lines from the worker starting up.
[src:dramatiq/guide] Look for lines containing the string `[dramatiq.MainProcess]`.
[src:dramatiq/guide] Sending `SIGHUP` to the workers every time you make a change is going to get old quick.
[src:dramatiq/guide] Instead, you can run the command line utility with the `--watch` flag pointing to the folder it should watch for source code changes.
[src:dramatiq/guide] Although this is a handy feature to use when developing your code, you should avoid using it in production!
[src:dramatiq/guide] As mentioned in the error handling section, Dramatiq automatically retries failures with exponential backoff.
[src:dramatiq/guide] You can specify how failures should be retried on a per-actor basis.
[src:dramatiq/guide] Instead of limiting the number of times messages can be retried, you might want to expire old messages.
[src:dramatiq/guide] Once a message has exceeded its retry or age limits, it gets moved to the dead letter queue where it’s kept for up to 7 days and then automatically dropped from the message broker.
[src:dramatiq/guide] From here, you can manually inspect the message and decide whether or not it should be put back on the queue.
[src:dramatiq/guide] In `count_words`, we didn’t set an explicit timeout for the outbound request which means that it can take a very long time to complete if the server we’re requesting is timing out.
[src:dramatiq/guide] Dramatiq has a default actor time limit of 10 minutes, which means that any actor running for longer than 10 minutes is killed with a `TimeLimitExceeded` error.
[src:dramatiq/guide] While this will keep our actor from running forever, remember that you should take care to always specify a timeout for the request itself, and this is **not** a good way to handle request timeouts in production code.
[src:dramatiq/guide] They cannot cancel system calls or any function that doesn’t currently hold the GIL under CPython.
[src:dramatiq/guide] For more information, see the section on Message Interrupts.
[src:dramatiq/guide] Keep in mind that *your message broker is not a database*.
[src:dramatiq/guide] Scheduled messages should represent a small subset of all your messages.
[src:dramatiq/guide] Say your app has some actors that are higher priority than others: for example, actors that affect your UI and make users wait, or are otherwise user-facing, versus actors that aren’t.
[src:dramatiq/guide] When choosing between multiple messages to run, Dramatiq will run the message that belongs to the actor with the highest priority.
[src:dramatiq/guide] Actor priority only takes effect when Dramatiq is choosing which message to run.
[src:dramatiq/guide] This only happens *after* messages are consumed from the queues.
[src:dramatiq/guide] The actory priority option has **no effect on messages while they are waiting in a queue**.
[src:dramatiq/guide] It only applies once messaged are consumed from the queues, and are waiting in-memory to be processed.
[src:dramatiq/guide] That way if messages for both `generate_report` and `sync_order_to_warehouse` have been consumed from the queue at the same time but there’s only capacity to run one of them, `generate_report` will always run *first*.
[src:dramatiq/guide] The lower the numeric value, the higher priority!
[src:dramatiq/guide] If you need a mnemonic to remember this, think of having a ticket with a number on it handed to you while waiting in line, perhaps at a government institution or deli counter.
[src:dramatiq/guide] Because actor `priority` does not effect messages waiting in the queues, it is most useful for making Dramatiq treat certain queues as higher priority than others.
[src:dramatiq/guide] To make this work best, all the actors for a queue should have the same actor `priority`.
[src:dramatiq/guide] The `RabbitmqBroker` supports prioritizing messages while they are waiting in the queue with the `broker_priority` option.
[src:dramatiq/guide] Dramatiq abstracts over the notion of a message broker and currently supports both RabbitMQ and Redis out of the box.
[src:dramatiq/guide] By default, it’ll set up a RabbitMQ broker instance pointing at the local host.
[src:dramatiq/guide] Dramatiq provides a `StubBroker` that can be used in unit tests so you don’t have to have a running RabbitMQ or Redis instance in order to run your tests.
[src:dramatiq/guide] Because all actors are callable, you can of course also unit test them synchronously by calling them as you would normal functions.
[src:dramatiq/guide] By default, any exceptions raised by an actor are caught by the worker, which runs in a separate thread from the one your tests run in.
[src:dramatiq/guide] This means that any exceptions your actor throws will not be immediately visible to your test code!
[src:dramatiq/guide] This way, whatever exception caused the actor to fail will be raised eagerly within your test.
[src:dramatiq/guide] Note that the exception will only be raised once the actor exceeds its available retries.
[src:dramatiq/message-queue] In computer science, **message queues** and **mailboxes** are software-engineering components typically used for inter-process communication (IPC), or for inter-thread communication within the same process.
[src:dramatiq/message-queue] They use a queue for messaging – the passing of control or of content.
[src:dramatiq/message-queue] Group communication systems provide similar kinds of functionality.
[src:dramatiq/message-queue] The message queue paradigm is a sibling of the publisher/subscriber pattern, and is typically one part of a larger message-oriented middleware system.
[src:dramatiq/message-queue] Most messaging systems support both the publisher/subscriber and message queue models in their API, e.g.
[src:dramatiq/message-queue] Competing Consumers pattern enables multiple concurrent consumers to process messages on the same message queue.
[src:dramatiq/message-queue] Message queues implement an asynchronous communication pattern between two or more processes/threads whereby the sending and receiving party do not need to interact with the message queue at the same time.
[src:dramatiq/message-queue] Messages placed onto the queue are stored until the recipient retrieves them.
[src:dramatiq/message-queue] Message queues have implicit or explicit limits on the size of data that may be transmitted in a single message and the number of messages that may remain outstanding on the queue.
[src:dramatiq/message-queue] Many implementations of message queues function internally within an operating system or within an application.
[src:dramatiq/message-queue] Such queues exist for the purposes of that system only.
[src:dramatiq/message-queue] Other implementations allow the passing of messages between different computer systems, potentially connecting multiple applications and multiple operating systems.
[src:dramatiq/message-queue] These message queuing systems typically provide resilience functionality to ensure that messages do not get "lost" in the event of a system failure.
[src:dramatiq/message-queue] Examples of commercial implementations of this kind of message queuing software (also known as message-oriented middleware) include IBM MQ (formerly MQ Series) and Oracle Advanced Queuing (AQ).
[src:dramatiq/message-queue] There is a Java standard called Java Message Service, which has several proprietary and free software implementations.
[src:dramatiq/message-queue] Real-time operating systems (RTOSes) such as VxWorks and QNX encourage the use of message queuing as the primary inter-process or inter-thread communication mechanism.
[src:dramatiq/message-queue] This can result in integration between message passing and CPU scheduling.
[src:dramatiq/message-queue] Early examples of commercial RTOSes that encouraged a message-queue basis to inter-thread communication also include VRTX and pSOS+, both of which date to the early 1980s.
[src:dramatiq/message-queue] The Erlang programming language uses *processes* to provide concurrency; these processes communicate asynchronously using message queuing.
[src:dramatiq/message-queue] The message queue software can be either proprietary, open source or a mix of both.
[src:dramatiq/message-queue] It is then run either on premise in private servers or on external cloud servers (message queuing service).
[src:dramatiq/message-queue] Examples on hardware-based messaging middleware vendors are Solace, Apigee, and IBM MQ.
[src:dramatiq/message-queue] In a typical message-queueing implementation, a system administrator installs and configures message-queueing software (a queue manager or broker), and defines a named message queue.
[src:dramatiq/message-queue] Or they register with a message queuing service.
[src:dramatiq/message-queue] An application then registers a software routine that "listens" for messages placed onto the queue.
[src:dramatiq/message-queue] Second and subsequent applications may connect to the queue and transfer a message onto it.
[src:dramatiq/message-queue] The queue-manager software stores the messages until a receiving application connects and then calls the registered software routine.
[src:dramatiq/message-queue] The receiving application then processes the message in an appropriate manner.
[src:dramatiq/message-queue] These are all considerations that can have substantial effects on transaction semantics, system reliability, and system efficiency.
[src:dramatiq/message-queue] Historically, message queuing has used proprietary, closed protocols, restricting the ability for different operating systems or programming languages to interact in a heterogeneous set of environments.
[src:dramatiq/message-queue] An early attempt to make message queuing more ubiquitous was Sun Microsystems' JMS specification, which provided a Java-only abstraction of a client API.
[src:dramatiq/message-queue] This allowed Java developers to switch between providers of message queuing in a fashion similar to that of developers using SQL databases.
[src:dramatiq/message-queue] In practice, given the diversity of message queuing techniques and scenarios, this wasn't always as practical as it could be.
[src:dramatiq/message-queue] These protocols are at different stages of standardization and adoption.
[src:dramatiq/message-queue] The first two operate at the same level as HTTP, MQTT at the level of TCP/IP.
[src:dramatiq/message-queue] Some proprietary implementations also use HTTP to provide message queuing by some implementations, such as Amazon's SQS.
[src:dramatiq/message-queue] This is because it is always possible to layer asynchronous behaviour (which is what is required for message queuing) over a synchronous protocol using request-response semantics.
[src:dramatiq/message-queue] However, such implementations are constrained by the underlying protocol in this case and may not be able to offer the full fidelity or set of options required in message passing above.
[src:dramatiq/message-queue] Many of the more widely known communications protocols in use operate synchronously.
[src:dramatiq/message-queue] The HTTP protocol – used in the World Wide Web and in web services – offers an obvious example where a user sends a request for a web page and then waits for a reply.
[src:dramatiq/message-queue] However, scenarios exist in which synchronous behaviour is not appropriate.
[src:dramatiq/message-queue] For example, AJAX (Asynchronous JavaScript and XML) can be used to asynchronously send text, JSON or XML messages to update part of a web page with more relevant information.
[src:dramatiq/message-queue] Google uses this approach for their Google Suggest, a search feature which sends the user's partially typed queries to Google's servers and returns a list of possible full queries the user might be interested in the process of typing.
[src:dramatiq/message-queue] This list is asynchronously updated as the user types.
[src:dramatiq/message-queue] Other asynchronous examples exist in event notification systems and publish/subscribe systems.
[src:dramatiq/message-queue] In both of the above examples it would not make sense for the sender of the information to have to wait if, for example, one of the recipients had crashed.
[src:dramatiq/message-queue] Applications need not be exclusively synchronous or asynchronous.
[src:dramatiq/message-queue] In all these sorts of situations, having a subsystem which performs message-queuing (or alternatively, a broadcast messaging system) can help improve the behavior of the overall system.
[src:dramatiq/message-queue] There are two common message queue implementations in UNIX.
[src:dramatiq/message-queue] One is part of the SYS V API, the other one is part of POSIX.
[src:dramatiq/message-queue] UNIX SYS V implements message passing by keeping an array of linked lists as message queues.
[src:dramatiq/message-queue] Each message queue is identified by its index in the array, and has a unique descriptor.
[src:dramatiq/message-queue] A given index can have multiple possible descriptors.
[src:dramatiq/message-queue] UNIX gives standard functions to access the message passing feature.
[src:dramatiq/message-queue] This system call takes a key as an argument and returns a descriptor of the queue with the matching key if it exists.
[src:dramatiq/message-queue] flag is set, it makes a new message queue with the given key and returns its descriptor.
[src:dramatiq/message-queue] Used to receive a message from a given queue descriptor.
[src:dramatiq/message-queue] The caller process must have read permissions for the queue.
[src:dramatiq/message-queue] Used to change message queue parameters like the owner.
[src:dramatiq/message-queue] A message queue can be deleted only by its creator, owner, or the superuser.
[src:dramatiq/message-queue] The POSIX.1-2001 message queue API is the later of the two UNIX message queue APIs.
[src:dramatiq/message-queue] It is distinct from the SYS V API, but provides similar function.
[src:dramatiq/message-queue] The unix man page `mq_overview(7)` provides an overview of POSIX message queues.
[src:dramatiq/message-queue] Graphical user interfaces (GUIs) employ a message queue, also called an *event queue* or *input queue*, to pass graphical input actions, such as mouse clicks, keyboard events, or other user inputs, to the application program.
[src:dramatiq/message-queue] The windowing system places messages indicating user or other events, such as timer ticks or messages sent by other threads, into the message queue.
[src:dramatiq/message-queue] The GUI application removes these events one at a time by calling a routine called `getNextEvent()` or similar in an event loop, and then calling the appropriate application routine to process that event.
[src:dramatiq/motivation] Dramatiq’s primary reason for being is the fact that I wanted a distributed task queueing library that is simple and has sane defaults for most SaaS workloads.
[src:dramatiq/motivation] In that sense, it draws a lot of inspiration from GAE Push Queues and Sidekiq.
[src:dramatiq/motivation] If you’ve ever had to use Celery in anger, Dramatiq could be the tool for you.
[src:dramatiq/motivation] It’s possible that various bits of the table below are now outdated.
[src:dramatiq/motivation] Clarifications in PR form are always welcome!
[src:dramatiq/motivation] I’ve used Celery professionally for years and my growing frustration with it is one of the reasons why I developed dramatiq.
[src:dramatiq/producer-consumer-problem] In computing, the **producer-consumer problem** (also known as the **bounded-buffer problem**) is a family of problems described by Edsger W.
[src:dramatiq/producer-consumer-problem] Dijkstra wrote about the unbounded buffer case: "We consider two processes, which are called the 'producer' and the 'consumer' respectively.
[src:dramatiq/producer-consumer-problem] The producer is a cyclic process and each time it goes through its cycle it produces a certain portion of information, that has to be processed by the consumer.
[src:dramatiq/producer-consumer-problem] The consumer is also a cyclic process and each time it goes through its cycle, it can process the next portion of information, as has been produced by the producer ...
[src:dramatiq/producer-consumer-problem] He wrote about the bounded buffer case: "We have studied a producer and a consumer coupled via a buffer with unbounded capacity ...
[src:dramatiq/producer-consumer-problem] And about the multiple producer-consumer case: "We consider a number of producer/consumer pairs, where pairi is coupled via an information stream containing ni portions.
[src:dramatiq/producer-consumer-problem] Per Brinch Hansen and Niklaus Wirth saw soon the problem of semaphores: "I have come to the same conclusion with regard to semaphores, namely that they are not suitable for higher level languages.
[src:dramatiq/producer-consumer-problem] The original semaphore bounded buffer solution was written in ALGOL style.
[src:dramatiq/producer-consumer-problem] The buffer can store N portions or elements.
[src:dramatiq/producer-consumer-problem] The "number of queueing portions" semaphore counts the filled locations in the buffer, the "number of empty positions" semaphore counts the empty locations in the buffer and the semaphore "buffer manipulation" works as mutex for the buffer put and get operations.
[src:dramatiq/producer-consumer-problem] If the buffer is full, that is the number of empty positions is zero, the producer thread will wait in the P(number of empty positions) operation.
[src:dramatiq/producer-consumer-problem] If the buffer is empty, that is the number of queueing portions is zero, the consumer thread will wait in the P(number of queueing portions) operation.
[src:dramatiq/producer-consumer-problem] The V() operations release the semaphores.
[src:dramatiq/producer-consumer-problem] As a side effect, a thread can move from the wait queue to the ready queue.
[src:dramatiq/producer-consumer-problem] The P() operation decreases the semaphore value down to zero.
[src:dramatiq/producer-consumer-problem] The V() operation increases the semaphore value.
[src:dramatiq/producer-consumer-problem] As of C++ 20, semaphores are part of the language.
[src:dramatiq/producer-consumer-problem] Dijkstra's solution can easily be written in modern C++.
[src:dramatiq/producer-consumer-problem] The variable buffer_manipulation is a mutex.
[src:dramatiq/producer-consumer-problem] The semaphore feature of acquiring in one thread and releasing in another thread is not needed.
[src:dramatiq/producer-consumer-problem] The lock_guard() statement instead of a lock() and unlock() pair is C++ RAII.
[src:dramatiq/producer-consumer-problem] The lock_guard destructor ensures lock release in case of an exception.
[src:dramatiq/producer-consumer-problem] This solution can handle multiple consumer threads and/or multiple producer threads.
[src:dramatiq/producer-consumer-problem] Per Brinch Hansen defined the monitor: I will use the term monitor to denote a shared variable and the set of meaningful operations on it.
[src:dramatiq/producer-consumer-problem] The purpose of a monitor is to control the scheduling of resources among individual processes according to a certain policy.
[src:dramatiq/producer-consumer-problem] Tony Hoare laid a theoretical foundation for the monitor.
[src:dramatiq/producer-consumer-problem] The monitor is an object that contains variables `buffer`, `head`, `tail` and `count` to realize a circular buffer, the condition variables `nonempty` and `nonfull` for synchronization and the methods `append` and `remove` to access the bounded buffer.
[src:dramatiq/producer-consumer-problem] The monitor operation wait corresponds to the semaphore operation P or acquire, signal corresponds to V or release.
[src:dramatiq/producer-consumer-problem] The circled operation (+) are taken modulo N.
[src:dramatiq/producer-consumer-problem] The presented Pascal style pseudo code shows a Hoare monitor.
[src:dramatiq/producer-consumer-problem] A Mesa monitor uses `while count` instead of `if count`.
[src:dramatiq/producer-consumer-problem] The C++ version needs an additional mutex for technical reasons.
[src:dramatiq/producer-consumer-problem] It uses assert to enforce the preconditions for the buffer add and remove operations.
[src:dramatiq/producer-consumer-problem] The very first producer-consumer solution in the Electrologica computers used 'channels'.
[src:dramatiq/producer-consumer-problem] Hoare defined channels: An alternative to explicit naming of source and destination would be to name a port through which communication is to take place.
[src:dramatiq/producer-consumer-problem] The port names would be local to the processes, and the manner in which pairs of ports are to be connected by channels could be declared in the head of a parallel command.
[src:dramatiq/producer-consumer-problem] Brinch Hansen implemented channels in the programming languages Joyce and Super Pascal.
[src:dramatiq/producer-consumer-problem] The Plan 9 operating system programming language Alef, the Inferno operating system programming language Limbo have channels.
[src:dramatiq/producer-consumer-problem] The program entry point is at function `threadmain`.
[src:dramatiq/producer-consumer-problem] The function call `ch = chancreate(sizeof(ulong), 1)` creates the channel, the function call `sendul(ch, i)` sends a value into the channel and the function call `p = recvul(ch)` receives a value from the channel.
[src:dramatiq/producer-consumer-problem] The programming language Go has channels, too.
[src:dramatiq/producer-consumer-problem] The Go producer-consumer solution uses the main Go routine for consumer and creates a new, unnamed Go routine for the producer.
[src:dramatiq/producer-consumer-problem] The two Go routines are connected with channel ch.
[src:dramatiq/producer-consumer-problem] This channel can queue up to three int values.
[src:dramatiq/producer-consumer-problem] The statement `ch := make(chan int, 3)` creates the channel, the statement `ch <- produceMessage()` sends a value into the channel and the statement `recvMsg := range ch` receives a value from the channel.
[src:dramatiq/producer-consumer-problem] The allocation of memory resources, the allocation of processing resources, and the synchronization of resources are done by the programming language automatically.
[src:dramatiq/producer-consumer-problem] Leslie Lamport documented a bounded buffer producer-consumer solution for one producer and one consumer: We assume that the buffer can hold at most b messages, b >= 1.
[src:dramatiq/producer-consumer-problem] In our solution, we let k be a constant greater than b, and let s and r be integer variables assuming values between 0 and k-1.
[src:dramatiq/producer-consumer-problem] We assume that initially s=r and the buffer is empty.
[src:dramatiq/producer-consumer-problem] By choosing k to be a multiple of b, the buffer can be implemented as an array B [0: b - 1].
[src:dramatiq/producer-consumer-problem] The producer simply puts each new message into B[s mod b], and the consumer takes each message from B[r mod b].
[src:dramatiq/producer-consumer-problem] The algorithm is shown below, generalized for infinite k.
[src:dramatiq/producer-consumer-problem] The Lamport solution uses busy waiting in the thread instead of waiting in the scheduler.
[src:dramatiq/producer-consumer-problem] This solution neglects the impact of scheduler thread switch at inconvenient times.
[src:dramatiq/producer-consumer-problem] If the first thread has read a variable value from memory, the scheduler switches to the second thread that changes the variable value, and the scheduler switches back to the first thread then the first thread uses the old value of the variable, not the current value.
[src:dramatiq/producer-consumer-problem] Atomic read-modify-write solves this problem.
[src:dramatiq/producer-consumer-problem] Modern C++ offers `atomic` variables and operations for multi-thread programming.
[src:dramatiq/producer-consumer-problem] The following busy waiting C++11 solution for one producer and one consumer uses atomic read-modify-write operations `fetch_add` and `fetch_sub` on the atomic variable `count`.
[src:dramatiq/producer-consumer-problem] The circular buffer index variables `head` and `tail` are thread-local and therefore not relevant for memory consistency.
[src:dramatiq/producer-consumer-problem] The variable `count` controls the busy waiting of the producer and consumer thread.
[src:dramatiq/rabbitmq] Written in Erlang, the RabbitMQ server is built on the Open Telecom Platform framework for clustering and failover.
[src:dramatiq/rabbitmq] Client libraries to interface with the broker are available for all major programming languages.
[src:dramatiq/rabbitmq] The source code is released under the Mozilla Public License.
[src:dramatiq/rabbitmq] Originally developed by Rabbit Technologies Ltd. which started as a joint venture between LShift and CohesiveFT in 2007, RabbitMQ was acquired in April 2010 by SpringSource, a division of VMware.
[src:dramatiq/rabbitmq] The project became part of Pivotal Software in May 2013, which then got acquired back by VMware in December 2019.
[src:dramatiq/rabbitmq] This section gives sample programs written in Python (using the *pika* package) for sending and receiving messages using a queue.
[src:dramatiq/rabbitmq] The following code fragment establishes a connection, makes sure the recipient queue exists, then sends a message and finally closes the connection.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] In computing, **scheduling** is the action of assigning resources to perform tasks.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] The resources may be processors, network links or expansion cards.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] The tasks may be threads, processes or data flows.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] The scheduling activity is carried out by a mechanism called a **scheduler**.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] Schedulers are often designed so as to keep all computer resources busy (as in load balancing), allow multiple users to share system resources effectively, or to achieve a target quality-of-service.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] Scheduling is fundamental to computation itself, and an intrinsic part of the execution model of a computer system; the concept of scheduling makes it possible to have computer multitasking with a single central processing unit (CPU).
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] In practice, these goals often conflict (e.g. throughput versus latency), thus a scheduler will implement a suitable compromise.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] Preference is measured by any one of the concerns mentioned above, depending upon the user's needs and objectives.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] In real-time environments, such as embedded systems for automatic control in industry (for example robotics), the scheduler also must ensure that processes can meet deadlines; this is crucial for keeping the system stable.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] Scheduled tasks can also be distributed to remote devices across a network and managed through an administrative back end.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] The scheduler is an operating system module that selects the next jobs to be admitted into the system and the next process to run.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] Operating systems may feature up to three distinct scheduler types: a *long-term scheduler* (also known as an admission scheduler or high-level scheduler), a *mid-term or medium-term scheduler*, and a *short-term scheduler*.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] The names suggest the relative frequency with which their functions are performed.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] The process scheduler is a part of the operating system that decides which process runs at a certain point in time.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] It usually has the ability to pause a running process, move it to the back of the running queue and start a new process; such a scheduler is known as a *preemptive scheduler*.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] If the scheduler cannot pause a running process and start a new process, the scheduler is a *cooperative scheduler*.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] We distinguish between *long-term scheduling*, *medium-term scheduling*, and *short-term scheduling* based on how often decisions must be made.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] Thus, this scheduler dictates what processes are to run on a system, the degree of concurrency to be supported at any one time – whether many or few processes are to be executed concurrently, and how the split between I/O-intensive and CPU-intensive processes is to be handled.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] The long-term scheduler is responsible for controlling the degree of multiprogramming.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] In general, most processes can be described as either I/O-bound or CPU-bound.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] An I/O-bound process is one that spends more of its time doing I/O than it spends doing computations.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] A CPU-bound process, in contrast, generates I/O requests infrequently, using more of its time doing computations.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] It is important that a long-term scheduler selects a good process mix of I/O-bound and CPU-bound processes.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] If all processes are I/O-bound, the ready queue will almost always be empty, and the short-term scheduler will have little to do.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] On the other hand, if all processes are CPU-bound, the I/O waiting queue will almost always be empty, devices will go unused, and again the system will be unbalanced.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] The system with the best performance will thus have a combination of CPU-bound and I/O-bound processes.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] In modern operating systems, this is used to make sure that real-time processes get enough CPU time to finish their tasks.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] Long-term scheduling is also important in large-scale systems such as batch processing systems, computer clusters, supercomputers, and render farms.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] For example, in concurrent systems, coscheduling of interacting processes is often required to prevent them from blocking due to waiting on each other.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] In these cases, special-purpose job scheduler software is typically used to assist these functions, in addition to any underlying admission scheduling support in the operating system.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] Some operating systems only allow new tasks to be added if it is sure all real-time deadlines can still be met.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] The specific heuristic algorithm used by an operating system to accept or reject new tasks is the *admission control mechanism*.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] The *medium-term scheduler* temporarily removes processes from main memory and places them in secondary memory (such as a hard disk drive) or vice versa, which is commonly referred to as *swapping out* or *swapping in* (also incorrectly as *paging out* or *paging in*).
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] In many systems today (those that support mapping virtual address space to secondary storage other than the swap file), the medium-term scheduler may actually perform the role of the long-term scheduler, by treating binaries as *swapped-out processes* upon their execution.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] In this way, when a segment of the binary is required, it can be swapped in on demand, or *lazy loaded*, also called demand paging.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] The *short-term scheduler* (also known as the *CPU scheduler*) decides which of the ready, in-memory processes is to be executed (allocated a CPU) after a clock interrupt, an I/O interrupt, an operating system call or another form of signal.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] Thus, the short-term scheduler makes scheduling decisions much more frequently than the long-term or mid-term schedulers – A scheduling decision will, at a minimum, have to be made after every time slice, and these are very short.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] This scheduler can be preemptive, implying that it is capable of forcibly removing processes from a CPU when it decides to allocate that CPU to another process, or non-preemptive (also known as *voluntary* or *co-operative*), in which case the scheduler is unable to *force* processes off the CPU.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] Another component that is involved in the CPU-scheduling function is the dispatcher, which is the module that gives control of the CPU to the process selected by the short-term scheduler.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] It receives control in kernel mode as the result of an interrupt or system call.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] The dispatcher should be as fast as possible since it is invoked during every process switch.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] During the context switches, the processor is virtually idle for a fraction of time, thus unnecessary context switches should be avoided.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] The time it takes for the dispatcher to stop one process and start another is known as the *dispatch latency*.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] A **scheduling discipline** (also called **scheduling policy** or **scheduling algorithm**) is an algorithm used for distributing resources among parties that simultaneously and asynchronously request them.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] Scheduling disciplines are used in routers (to handle packet traffic) as well as in operating systems (to share CPU time among both threads and processes), disk drives (I/O scheduling), printers (print spooler), most embedded systems, etc.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] The main purposes of scheduling algorithms are to minimize resource starvation and to ensure fairness amongst the parties utilizing the resources.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] Scheduling deals with the problem of deciding which of the outstanding requests is to be allocated resources.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] There are many different scheduling algorithms.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] In this section, we introduce several of them.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] In packet-switched computer networks and other statistical multiplexing, the notion of a **scheduling algorithm** is used as an alternative to first-come first-served queuing of data packets.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] The simplest best-effort scheduling algorithms are round-robin, fair queuing (a max-min fair scheduling algorithm), proportional-fair scheduling and maximum throughput.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] If differentiated or guaranteed quality of service is offered, as opposed to best-effort communication, weighted fair queuing may be utilized.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] In advanced packet radio wireless networks such as HSDPA (High-Speed Downlink Packet Access) 3.5G cellular system, **channel-dependent scheduling** may be used to take advantage of channel state information.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] If the channel conditions are favourable, the throughput and system spectral efficiency may be increased.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] In even more advanced systems such as LTE, the scheduling is combined by channel-dependent packet-by-packet dynamic channel allocation, or by assigning OFDMA multi-carriers or other frequency-domain equalization components to the users that best can utilize them.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] Earliest deadline first (EDF) or *least time to go* is a dynamic scheduling algorithm used in real-time operating systems to place processes in a priority queue.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] Whenever a scheduling event occurs (a task finishes, a new task is released, etc.), the queue will be searched for the process closest to its deadline, which will be the next to be scheduled for execution.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] With this strategy the scheduler arranges processes with the least estimated processing time remaining to be next in the queue.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] This requires advanced knowledge or estimations about the time required for a process to complete.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] The operating system assigns a fixed-priority rank to every process, and the scheduler arranges the processes in the ready queue in order of their priority.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] Lower-priority processes get interrupted by incoming higher-priority processes.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] The scheduler assigns a fixed time unit per process, and cycles through them.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] If the process completes within that time slice, it gets terminated otherwise, it is rescheduled after giving a chance to all other processes.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] This is used for situations in which processes are easily divided into different groups.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] For example, a common division is made between foreground (interactive) processes and background (batch) processes.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] These two types of processes have different response-time requirements and so may have different scheduling needs.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] It is very useful for shared memory problems.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] A work-conserving scheduler is a scheduler that always tries to keep the scheduled resources busy if there are submitted jobs ready to be scheduled.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] In contrast, a non-work-conserving scheduler is a scheduler that, in some cases, may leave the scheduled resources idle despite the presence of jobs ready to be scheduled.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] A very common method in embedded systems is to schedule jobs manually.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] This can, for example, be done in a time-multiplexed fashion.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] Sometimes the kernel is divided in three or more parts: Manual scheduling, preemptive and interrupt level.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] Exact methods for scheduling jobs are often proprietary.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] When designing an operating system, a programmer must consider which scheduling algorithm will perform best for the use the system is going to see.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] There is no universal *best* scheduling algorithm, and many operating systems use extended or combinations of the scheduling algorithms above.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] For example, Windows NT/XP/Vista uses a multilevel feedback queue, a combination of fixed-priority preemptive scheduling, round-robin, and first-in, first-out algorithms.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] In this system, threads can dynamically increase or decrease in priority depending on if it has been serviced already or if it has been waiting extensively.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] Every priority level is represented by its own queue, with round-robin scheduling among the high-priority threads and FIFO among the lower-priority ones.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] In this sense, response time is short for most threads, and short but critical system threads get completed very quickly.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] Since threads can only use one time unit of the round-robin in the highest-priority queue, starvation can be a problem for longer high-priority threads.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] The algorithm used may be as simple as round-robin in which each process is given equal time (for instance, 1 ms, usually between 1 ms and 100 ms) in a cycling list.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] So, process A executes for 1 ms, then process B, then process C, then back to process A.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] More advanced algorithms take into account process priority, or the importance of the process.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] This allows some processes to use more time than others.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] The kernel always uses whatever resources it needs to ensure proper functioning of the system, and so can be said to have infinite priority.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] In SMP systems, processor affinity is considered to increase overall system performance, even if it may cause a process itself to run more slowly.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] This generally improves performance by reducing cache thrashing.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] IBM OS/360 was available with three different schedulers.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] Later virtual storage versions of MVS added a *Workload Manager* feature to the scheduler, which schedules processor resources according to an elaborate scheme defined by the installation.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] Very early MS-DOS and Microsoft Windows systems were non-multitasking, and as such did not feature a scheduler.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] Windows 3.1x used a non-preemptive scheduler, meaning that it did not interrupt programs.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] It relied on the program to end or tell the OS that it didn't need the processor so that it could move on to another process.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] This is usually called cooperative multitasking.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] Windows 95 introduced a rudimentary preemptive scheduler; however, for legacy support opted to let 16-bit applications run without preemption.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] Windows NT-based operating systems use a multilevel feedback queue.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] 32 priority levels are defined, 0 through 31, with priorities 0 through 15 being *normal* priorities and priorities 16 through 31 being soft real-time priorities, requiring privileges to assign.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] User interfaces and APIs work with priority classes for the process and the threads in the process, which are then combined by the system into the absolute priority level.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] The scheduler was modified in Windows Vista to use the cycle counter register of modern processors to keep track of exactly how many CPU cycles a thread has executed, rather than just using an interval-timer interrupt routine.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] Vista also uses a priority scheduler for the I/O queue so that disk defragmenters and other such programs do not interfere with foreground operations.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] Mac OS 9 uses cooperative scheduling for threads, where one process controls multiple cooperative threads, and also provides preemptive scheduling for multiprocessing tasks.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] The kernel schedules multiprocessing tasks using a preemptive scheduling algorithm.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] All Process Manager processes run within a special multiprocessing task, called the *blue task*.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] Those processes are scheduled cooperatively, using a round-robin scheduling algorithm; a process yields control of the processor to another process by explicitly calling a blocking function such as `WaitNextEvent`.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] Each process has its own copy of the Thread Manager that schedules that process's threads cooperatively; a thread yields control of the processor to another thread by calling `YieldToAnyThread` or `YieldToThread`.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] macOS uses a multilevel feedback queue, with four priority bands for threads – normal, system high priority, kernel mode only, and real-time.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] Threads are scheduled preemptively; macOS also supports cooperatively scheduled threads in its implementation of the Thread Manager in Carbon.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] Threads are primarily of interest for applications that currently consist of several asynchronous processes.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] These applications might impose a lighter load on the system if converted to a multithreaded structure.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] AIX 5 implements the following scheduling policies: FIFO, round robin, and fair round robin.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] The FIFO policy has three different implementations: FIFO, FIFO2, and FIFO3.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] The round robin policy is named SCHED_RR in AIX, and the fair round robin is called SCHED_OTHER.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] Linux 1.2 used a round-robin scheduling policy.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] Linux 2.2 added scheduling classes and support for symmetric multiprocessing (SMP).
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] In Linux 2.4, an O(n) scheduler with a multilevel feedback queue with priority levels ranging from 0 to 140 was used; 0–99 are reserved for real-time tasks and 100–140 are considered nice task levels.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] For real-time tasks, the time quantum for switching processes was approximately 200 ms, and for nice tasks approximately 10 ms.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] The scheduler ran through the run queue of all ready processes, letting the highest priority processes go first and run through their time slices, after which they will be placed in an expired queue.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] When the active queue is empty, the expired queue will become the active queue and vice versa.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] However, some enterprise Linux distributions such as SUSE Linux Enterprise Server replaced this scheduler with a backport of the O(1) scheduler (which was maintained by Alan Cox in his Linux 2.4-ac Kernel series) to the Linux 2.4 kernel used by the distribution.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] In versions 2.6.0 to 2.6.22, the kernel used an O(1) scheduler developed by Ingo Molnar and many other kernel developers during the Linux 2.5 development.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] For many kernels in this time frame, Con Kolivas developed patch sets which improved interactivity with this scheduler or even replaced it with his own schedulers.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] Con Kolivas' work, most significantly his implementation of fair scheduling named Rotating Staircase Deadline (RSDL), inspired Ingo Molnár to develop the Completely Fair Scheduler (CFS) as a replacement for the earlier O(1) scheduler, crediting Kolivas in his announcement.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] CFS is the first implementation of a fair queuing process scheduler widely used in a general-purpose operating system.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] The CFS uses a well-studied, classic scheduling algorithm called fair queuing originally invented for packet networks.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] Fair queuing had been previously applied to CPU scheduling under the name stride scheduling.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] The fair queuing CFS scheduler has a scheduling complexity of $O(\log N)$ , where N is the number of tasks in the runqueue.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] Choosing a task can be done in constant time, but reinserting a task after it has run requires $O(\log N)$ operations, because the run queue is implemented as a red–black tree.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] The Brain Fuck Scheduler, also created by Con Kolivas, is an alternative to the CFS.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] In 2023, Peter Zijlstra proposed replacing CFS with an earliest eligible virtual deadline first scheduling (EEVDF) process scheduler.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] The aim was to remove the need for CFS *latency nice* patches.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] Linux 6.12 added support for scheduler extensions that can be added from userspace; this mechanism is known as sched_ext.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] An eBPF program can be loaded into the kernel to implement a scheduling policy.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] These schedulers can replace the default scheduler.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] FreeBSD uses a multilevel feedback queue with priorities ranging from 0–255.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] 0–63 are reserved for interrupts, 64–127 for the top half of the kernel, 128–159 for real-time user threads, 160–223 for time-shared user threads, and 224–255 for idle user threads.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] Also, like Linux, it uses the active queue setup, but it also has an idle queue.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] NetBSD uses a multilevel feedback queue with priorities ranging from 0–223.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] 0–63 are reserved for time-shared threads (default, SCHED_OTHER policy), 64–95 for user threads that entered kernel space, 96–128 for kernel threads, 128–191 for user real-time threads (SCHED_FIFO and SCHED_RR policies), and 192–223 for software interrupts.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] Solaris uses a multilevel feedback queue with priorities ranging between 0 and 169.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] Priorities 0–59 are reserved for time-shared threads, 60–99 for system threads, 100–159 for real-time threads, and 160–169 for low priority interrupts.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] Unlike Linux, when a process is done using its time quantum, it is given a new priority and put back in the queue.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] Solaris 9 introduced two new scheduling classes, namely fixed-priority class and fair share class.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] The threads with fixed priority have the same priority range as that of the time-sharing class, but their priorities are not dynamically adjusted.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] The fair scheduling class uses CPU *shares* to prioritize threads for scheduling decisions.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] CPU shares indicate the entitlement to CPU resources.
[src:dramatiq/task-queue] They are allocated to a set of processes, which are collectively known as a project.
